es. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":20,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705197,"age":93,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"Agnes Greenacres was born in 1362, in Lancashire, England as the daughter of Richard Greenacres. She had at least 1 son with William Radcliffe."},"et":{"1362–":"1362–Surnud","1362–Female":"1362–Surnud","1348–1422":"1348–1422","1410–Male":"1410–Surnud","1340–Male":"1340–Surnud","1348":"1348","1455":"1455","1422":"1422","1410":"1410","1362":"1362","1340":"1340","about 1410":"umbes 1410","1382":"1382","Great Marley, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Wymersley, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England"},"fi":{"1362–":"1362–Kuollut","